item.description: In recent weeks, Toys “R” Us announced the closure of 735 U.S. stores (an event The Simpsons predicted in 2004). Now, the company’s founder, Charles Lazarus, has died. Although the 94-year-old had no stake in the company, he started the business in 1948 at 25. He sold baby furniture in a store called Children’s Bargain Store in Washington, D.C., then quickly expanded to selling toys, CNN reports. Lazarus opened his first store in 1957 and provided customers with whimsical experiences as they shopped for trinkets.
